  "Raising the freezing point of the coolant liquid": "",
  "Lowering the freezing point and raising the boiling point of coolant": "",
  "Replacing water entirely so there is nothing to freeze": "",
  "Generating heat to keep the engine at operating temperature": "",
  "Antifreeze (ethylene glycol) mixed with water lowers the freezing point (prevents freezing in winter) and raises the boiling point (prevents overheating in summer).": "",
  "What is a colligative property?": "",
  "A property that depends on the identity of the solute particles": "",
  "A property that depends on the number of solute particles in solution": "",
  "A property that describes the color of a solution when dissolved": "",
  "A property that measures the mass of the solvent only in solution": "",
  "A colligative property is a physical property of a solution that depends on the concentration (number) of solute particles, regardless of what the solute is.": "",
  "What is boiling point elevation?": "",
  "The decrease in boiling point caused by adding solute particles": "",
  "The increase in boiling point caused by adding solute particles": "",
  "The boiling point of pure water at standard atmospheric pressure": "",
  "The temperature at which a solution begins to freeze into solid": "",
  "Boiling point elevation is the increase in the boiling point of a solvent when a non-volatile solute is dissolved in it. More solute particles cause a greater elevation.": "",
  "What is freezing point depression?": "",
  "The increase in freezing point when solute is dissolved in solvent": "",
  "The decrease in freezing point when solute is dissolved in solvent": "",
  "The temperature where pure solvent freezes at normal pressure": "",
  "The process of removing all solute from a frozen solution sample": "",
  "Freezing point depression is the lowering of the freezing point of a solvent when a solute is added. The solute particles disrupt crystal formation.": "",
  "What is osmosis?": "",
  "The movement of solute from low to high concentration through a membrane": "",
  "The movement of solvent from low to high solute concentration through a semipermeable membrane": "",
  "The evaporation of solvent from the surface of a solution in open air": "",
  "The dissolving of a solute in a solvent to form a homogeneous mixture": "",
  "Osmosis is the movement of solvent molecules through a semipermeable membrane from a region of lower solute concentration to higher solute concentration.": "",
  "What is vapor pressure?": "",
  "The pressure exerted by the dissolved solute at the bottom of solution": "",
  "The pressure exerted by the gas phase of a substance above its liquid": "",
  "The pressure needed to compress a gas into a liquid state of matter": "",
  "The atmospheric pressure measured at sea level on a standard day": "",
  "Vapor pressure is the pressure exerted by the gas (vapor) of a substance in equilibrium with its liquid phase. Adding solute reduces vapor pressure.": "",
  "What does 'non-volatile' mean regarding a solute?": "",
  "The solute easily evaporates from the solution at room temperature": "",
  "The solute does not easily evaporate and stays dissolved in the solution": "",
  "The solute reacts violently when mixed with the solvent material": "",
  "The solute is always a gas at standard room temperature and pressure": "",
  "A non-volatile solute has a very low vapor pressure and does not easily evaporate. Salt and sugar are non-volatile solutes that remain in solution when the solvent evaporates.": "",
  "What is a 'semipermeable membrane'?": "",
  "A barrier that allows all substances to pass through it freely": "",
  "A barrier that allows solvent to pass through but blocks solute particles": "",
  "A barrier that allows solute to pass but completely blocks all solvent": "",
  "A barrier that blocks everything and allows nothing to pass through": "",
  "A semipermeable membrane selectively allows some substances (typically small solvent molecules) to pass through while blocking larger solute particles.": "",
  "What does 'dissociation' mean for ionic solutes in solution?": "",
  "The ionic compound stays together as a whole formula unit in solution": "",
  "The ionic compound separates into individual ions when it dissolves": "",
  "The ionic compound reacts with water to form a completely new compound": "",
  "The ionic compound evaporates from the solution into the air above": "",
  "Dissociation is when an ionic compound separates into its individual ions in solution. NaCl dissociates into Na+ and Cl-, producing 2 particles per formula unit.": "",
  "What is the 'van't Hoff factor' (i)?": "",
  "The mass of solute needed to make exactly one molar solution": "",
  "The number of particles a solute produces when it dissolves": "",
  "The temperature at which a solution reaches its boiling point": "",
  "The volume of solvent needed to dissolve one mole of a solute": "",
  "The van't Hoff factor (i) represents the number of particles a solute produces in solution. For NaCl, i = 2 (Na+ and Cl-). For glucose, i = 1 (does not dissociate).": "",
  "What is Raoult's Law?": "",
  "Gas solubility is proportional to gas pressure above the solution": "",
  "The vapor pressure of a solution is reduced by the mole fraction of solute": "",
  "The boiling point of a solution equals twice the pure solvent boiling point": "",
  "Solubility of solids always increases with increasing temperature": "",
  "Raoult's Law states that the vapor pressure of a solution is proportional to the mole fraction of the solvent. Adding solute reduces the vapor pressure proportionally.": "",
  "A student adds salt to a pot of boiling water for pasta and notices the water momentarily stops boiling. What colligative property explains this?": "",
  "Freezing point depression caused by the added salt particles": "",
  "Boiling point elevation caused by the dissolved salt particles": "",
  "Vapor pressure increase caused by the salt dissolving in water": "",
  "The salt absorbed heat from the water making it too cool to boil": "",
  "Adding salt raises the boiling point (boiling point elevation). The water that was just at its boiling point is now below the new, higher boiling point, so it stops boiling momentarily.": "",
  "A student spreads salt on an icy sidewalk and the ice melts even though the temperature is -5 degrees C. What colligative property is at work?": "",
  "Boiling point elevation caused the ice to melt from heat": "",
  "Freezing point depression lowered the freezing point below -5 degrees C": "",
  "Osmotic pressure pushed water out of the ice crystal structure": "",
  "The salt generated chemical heat that melted the ice directly": "",
  "Salt causes freezing point depression. When salt dissolves in the thin layer of water on ice, it lowers the freezing point below the air temperature, causing the ice to melt.": "",
